{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"27ca08f3-af16-4725-8d4e-5b04f66b2aa3","content":"The repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, but I can answer from general .NET/macOS knowledge:\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS stores them in `/cores/` by default):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash** — run your NativeAOT app. macOS will write a `core.<pid>` file to `/cores/`.\n\n4. **If `/cores/` is empty**, check that SIP isn't blocking dumps:\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.coredump        # should be 1\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile        # shows path pattern\n   ```\n\n5. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n   Then use `bt` (backtrace), `thread list`, `frame variable`, etc.\n\n6. **Alternative — use macOS Crash Reporter logs** found at:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These `.ips` / `.crash` files are generated automatically and contain stack traces, even without core dumps enabled.\n\n**Key point:** Since NativeAOT apps don't bundle `createdump` (that's a CoreCLR tool), you rely on the OS-level core dump mechanism or the macOS Crash Reporter.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a8659f17-7882-4f70-ba9c-a78f91d38ffd","outputTokens":375,"requestId":"6406:C174F:150D888:1892548:69EC1A64"},"id":"439a0334-cb6b-4455-a883-963f72a5dddf","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:35:41.629Z","parentId":"07ce1113-445b-4477-ab48-6617793ca314"}
